    <string name="tip_general_pronunciation">Pay attention to the stress pattern in this word.</string>
    <string name="tip_th_sound">The \"th\" sound is made by placing your tongue between your teeth.</string>
    <string name="tip_r_sound">The English \"r\" sound is different from the Hindi \"र\" sound.</string>
    <string name="tip_l_sound">Make sure to pronounce the \"l\" sound clearly, different from \"र\".</string>
    <string name="tip_w_sound">For the \"w\" sound, round your lips more than for the Hindi \"व\".</string>
    <string name="tip_v_sound">For the \"v\" sound, touch your bottom lip to your upper teeth.</string>
    <string name="tip_sh_sound">The \"sh\" sound is similar to Hindi \"श\".</string>
    <string name="tip_ch_sound">The \"ch\" sound is similar to Hindi \"च\".</string>
    <string name="tip_j_sound">The \"j\" sound is similar to Hindi \"ज\".</string>
    <string name="tip_a_sound">The \"a\" vowel in English is often pronounced differently than in Hindi.</string>
    <string name="tip_e_sound">The \"e\" vowel in English is often pronounced as \"ए\" or \"इ\" in Hindi.</string>
    <string name="tip_i_sound">The \"i\" vowel in English can be short like \"इ\" or long like \"ई\".</string>
    <string name="tip_o_sound">The \"o\" vowel in English is often pronounced as \"ओ\" or \"आ\" in Hindi.</string>
    <string name="tip_u_sound">The \"u\" vowel in English can be short like \"उ\" or long like \"ऊ\".</string>
    <string name="tip_listen_carefully">Listen carefully to the pronunciation and try to mimic it exactly.</string>
    
